    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-06-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-06-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="228"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d228">
                <head>228. National Security Decision Memorandum 170<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d228fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG1"
                            >RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_FT1">FT</gloss>
                        1 <gloss target="#t_CHICOMS1">CHICOM</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_US1"
                            >US</gloss>. Secret; <gloss target="#t_NODIS1">Nodis</gloss>; Homer. The
                        typewritten date on this memorandum, June 10, was changed by hand. Also
                        issued as a Council on International Economic Policy Decision
                        Memorandum.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1972-06-08">June 8, 1972</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Treasury</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Agriculture</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Commerce</item>
                    <item>The Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss>
                        Trade</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has reviewed the memorandum submitted by the Department of State,
                    with the Department of Commerce, on April 24 and the response to <gloss
                        target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 149 submitted by the Ad Hoc Group on <pb
                        facs="0958" n="903" xml:id="pg_903"/> March 24 on the above subject.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d228fn2">On April 24 <persName corresp="#p_BWG1"
                            >Brown</persName> forwarded to <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> a covering memorandum and an 8-page report on
                        recommendations for implementing <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 149.
                        (National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files
                        1970–73, <gloss target="#t_FT1">FT</gloss> 1 <gloss target="#t_CHICOMS1"
                            >CHICOM</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>) Regarding the March
                        24 response to <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 149, see <ref
                            target="#d217">Documents 217</ref> and <ref target="#d219">219</ref>.
                            <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 149 is printed as <ref
                            target="#d208">Document 208</ref>.</note> Based on these, he has
                    approved the recommendations for actions over the next three months contained in
                    the April 24 memorandum for proceeding to implement the statement on trade in
                    the Shanghai communiqué with the following modifications: <list>
                        <item>—The memorandum for Ambassador <persName>Huang</persName> should
                            indicate that we recognize the <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss>’s
                            interest in MFN but view this as a subject for later discussion.<note
                                n="3" xml:id="d228fn3">See <ref target="#d242">Document
                                242</ref>.</note>
                        </item>
                        <item>—The matter of alleged <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> failure to
                            repay Export-Import Bank debt should not be raised by the <gloss
                                target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> at this time. An interagency committee
                            chaired by Treasury should examine this question and its effect on
                                <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> eligibility for Export-Import
                            Bank financing, and submit a report to the President by July 3. —The
                            memorandum for Ambassador <persName>Huang</persName> should place
                            greater stress on the necessity of beginning discussions in the near
                            future on the settlement of the claims issue.</item>
                        <item>—References to the cotton textile issue and to <gloss target="#t_US1"
                                >US</gloss> anti-dumping regulations and <gloss target="#t_US1"
                                >US</gloss> prohibitions on imports of “certain endangered animal
                            species” should be removed from the memorandum for Ambassador
                                <persName>Huang</persName>. These matters should be dealt with in
                            separate memoranda to be presented to Ambassador
                                <persName>Huang</persName> within the next several weeks. In his
                            oral presentation, Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_WAK1"
                                >Watson</persName> should indicate that we intend to provide the
                                <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> with such memoranda shortly.
                            Memoranda on these subjects together with recommendations as to the
                            timing of their presentation should be submitted to the President by
                            June 23.<note n="4" xml:id="d228fn4">Approved by <persName
                                    corresp="#p_HBGAMJ1">Haig</persName> in the White House and sent
                                as telegram 150506 to Paris, August 17. (Memorandum from <persName
                                    corresp="#p_HRD1">Hormats</persName> to <persName
                                    corresp="#p_HBGAMJ1">Haig</persName>, August 14, with attached
                                telegram; National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                                    >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                                    target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 529, Country Files, Far
                                East, Homer, <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>–<gloss
                                    target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> Negotiations, Paris)</note>
                        </item>
                        <item>—No mention should be made to the <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss>
                            at this time of possible <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> changes in
                            transportation regulations. The Department of State, in cooperation with
                            other appropriate agencies, should submit to the President as soon as
                            possible documents necessary to revise <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>
                            regulations regarding reciprocal visits by ships and aircraft. A draft
                            statement announcing such decisions as well as a statement indicating
                            that eventual establishment of scheduled air services would be subject
                            to <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss>
                            inter-Governmental discussions should also be submitted.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>As to recommendations for longer term steps, the President has deferred his
                    decision and requests that they be resubmitted with <pb facs="0959" n="904"
                        xml:id="pg_904"/> proposed memoranda, where appropriate, and specific
                    recommendations as to timing.<note n="5" xml:id="d228fn5">On June 12 <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> and Flanigan sent a memorandum to
                            <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_LMR1">Laird</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_PPG1"
                            >Peterson</persName>, and NASA Administrator Dr. <persName>James C.
                            Fletcher</persName> announcing that “in the review taking place on
                            <gloss target="#t_COCOM1">COCOM</gloss> the United States should adopt
                        as a general principle the termination of differential treatment for the
                            <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> as the basis for development of the
                        United States negotiating position. In the event that there are particular
                        items which we and other <gloss target="#t_COCOM1">COCOM</gloss> countries
                        agree should be treated on a differential basis, we should endeavor to apply
                        the concept of ‘disguised differential.’” (Ibid., Box 525, Country Files,
                        Far East, <gloss target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss>, Vol. IV)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <lb/> PMF</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
